Deploy your code on a Docker Container using Jenkins on AWS

Step by step process:
Jenkins server:
	Create Ec2 instance enable Jenkins port 8080 this is for jenkinsserver
	Inside EC2 install java, Jenkins , maven , git
	In Jenkins install github and mvn plugin
	In Jenkins under tools install mvn , java and git 
Docker server:
	Create EC2
	Install docker on that EC2
	Enable docker service install apache server on docker 
	In ec2 under security inbound role enable port 8081-9000
	Install tomcat server on docker manually as well as using docker file 
Integrate docker with Jenkins server :
	Create dockeradmin
	Install publish overSSH in Jenkins via Jenkins plugin
	Configure mkdir -p /home/dockeradmin/.ssh
	Ii) sudo nano /home/dockeradmin/.ssh/authorized_keys
	In this dockeradmin/.ssh  paste key from Jenkins server cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa system add SSH server
Create Jenkins Job to Build and Copy Artifacts on to Docker Host :
	Switch Ubuntu on docker host: ssh ubuntu@13.204.251.39
	Create .ssh directory and authorized keys 
	I) sudo
	.pub ( Before create a key from Jenkins by running ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "jenkins")
	Set permission:
sudo chown -R dockeradmin:dockeradmin /home/dockeradmin/.ssh
sudo chmod 700 /home/dockeradmin/.ssh
sudo chmod 600 /home/dockeradmin/.ssh/authorized_keys
	Test login on Jenkins server : ssh dockeradmin@13.204.251.39
	In Jenkins create a key ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096
	View the key by : cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
	Paste it in docker like this echo "ssh-key-here" | sudo tee -a /home/dockeradmin/.ssh/authorized_keys > /dev/null
	From this Jenkins server get private key sudo cat /var/lib/jenkins/.ssh/id_rsa   and paste this key under Jenkins system configuration  under SSH  under key  then test the connection 


